  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Understanding customer business activities\n- Assessing potential money laundering risks\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Notifying authorities about potential financial crimes\n\n3. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Documenting customer identification information\n- Retaining records for specified periods\n\n4. Compliance Programs\n- Implementing anti-money laundering (AML) policies\n- Training employees on detection and prevention\n- Establishing internal monitoring systems\n\n5. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying high-risk customers and transactions\n- Conducting ongoing monitoring\n- Implementing enhanced due diligence for complex cases\n\n6. International Regulations\n- Following guidelines from organizations like FATF\n- Complying with international anti-money laundering standards\n- Participating in global information sharing\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, including substantial fines and potential criminal charges.\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial institutions from being used as conduits for illegal financial activities.",
